SIMPLE: dotterel
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dotterel
<hw>Dot"ter*el</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Dottard</er>.]</ety> <def>Decayed.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Some old
<xex>dotterel</xex> trees.⟦rdquo⟧ <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Ascham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dotterel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dotterel
<hw>Dot"ter*el</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Dote</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A European bird of
the Plover family (<spn>Eudromias morinellus</spn>, syn. <spn>Charadrius
morinellus</spn>). It is tame and easily taken, and is popularly
believed to imitate the movements of the fowler.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In catching of <qex>dotterels</qex> we see how the foolish bird
playeth the ape in gestures.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The ringed dotterel (or ring plover) is
<stype><spn>Charadrius hiaticula</spn></stype>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A silly fellow; a dupe; a gull.</def>
<rj><au>Barrow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dotting pen</ent>⟦br⟧
